From @realmoney Netflix Talk $NFLX I do not have a dog in the Netflix hunt. Netflix had a terrific quarter but problems for anyone willing to look for some (which few are):
* Valuation: The company's market cap is now over $180 billion. This is almost at the level of Disney which has 10x the cash flow. The EBITD multiple is over 100x trailing twelve month EBITD.

* Content Spending: Content assets increased well more than $3 billion in one quarter! One could look at content on the balance sheet like a retailer’s inventory. It doesn’t improve with age. Eventually it will have to go through the income statement.

* Marketing spending: Up +39% and growing faster than sales. No scale economies so far. * Foreign subs are not domestic subs: Most costs are in dollars and there is risk if the U.S. dollar strengthens. An Indian sub is not equal to one in Indiana.

* Soaring interest expenses: Up +77% in the most recent quarter as net debt has soared to over $5 billion. Cash flow cover of gross interest is under 6x. Why use debt rather than (almost) free equity?

* Increasing competition: Disney, AT&T, Amazon (also cash flow not required). The loss of children’s content from Disney should really sting. $NFLX $DIS $AMZN @jimcramer @tomkeene @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC @carlquintanilla @andrewrsorkin

@realmoney Sis Boom Nah! There seems to be an ongoing narrative today in the business media that Netflix's quarterly results and the manner in which investors react to the print will be a referendum on FANG and other richly priced market sectors.
Some "talking heads are even stating that this report will govern the direction of the S&P Index. I have to disagree. I would go one step further - its nonsensical and a detour to reality.

Netflix has no resemblance fundamentally to Facebook, Amazon, Alphabet or any other high beta stock. Netflix has no peer and is unique in its business profile and in the set of metrics that it is judged by.

This, to me, is yet another example of business news hyperbole in which the airways are used to develop a hypothetical based on poorly reasoned commentary and narrative in order to ostensibly appeal to their audiences and attract new viewers. @jimcramer @tomkeene @carlquintanilla
